bald]] \u2013 Black & Decker\n|-\n|2014 \u2013 [[Elon Musk]] \u2013 Tesla, SpaceX\n|1995 \u2013 [[Robert Palmer (computer businessman)|Robert Palmer]] \u2013 Digital Corporation\n|-\n|2014 \u2013 [[Yang Yuanqing]] \u2013 Lenovo\n|1995 \u2013 [[Arthur C. Martinez|Arthur Martinez]] \u2013 Sears, Roebuck & Co.\n|-\n|2013 \u2013 [[Paul E. Jacobs]] \u2013 Qualcomm\n|1994 \u2013 H. John Greeniaus \u2013 Nabisco, Inc.\n|-\n|2012 \u2013 [[Chris Anderson (entrepreneur)|Chris Anderson]] \u2013 TED\n|1994 \u2013 Bert C. Roberts \u2013 MCI Corporation\n|-\n|2012 \u2013 [[Steve Jobs]] \u2013 Apple, Inc.\n|1993 \u2013 [[Bill_Marriott | J. Willard Marriott, Jr.]] \u2013 Marriott International\n|-\n|2011 \u2013 [[John S. Hendricks]] \u2013 Discovery Communications\n|1993 \u2013 [[Rich DeVos]] \u2013 Amway Corporation\n|-\n|2011 \u2013 [[Alan Mulally]] \u2013 Ford Motor Company\n|1993 \u2013 [[Jay Van Andel]] \u2013 Amway Corporation\n|-\n|2010 \u2013 [[Susan Hockfield]] \u2013 MIT\n|1993 \u2013 [[Raymond W. Smith]] \u2013 Bell Atlantic\n|-\n|2010 \u2013 [[A.G. Lafley]] \u2013 Procter & Gamble\n|1992 \u2013 [[William McGowan]] \u2013 MCI Corporation\n|-\n|2009 \u2013 [[David M. Kelley]] \u2013 IDEO\n|1991 \u2013 [[Frank Perdue]] \u2013 Perdue Farms\n|-\n|\n|1991 \u2013 [https://www.nytimes.com/1993/08/22/business/profile-herbert-m-baum-quaker-state-s-quick-change-artist.html Herb Baum] \u2013 Campbell Soup Co.\n|}\n\n==Edison Awards Steering Committee==\nSenior executives with diverse marketing, scientific, and business backgrounds serve on the Edison Awards [https://edisonawards.com/steering.php Steering Committee], overseeing the reviews of innovations submitted from around the world. After thoroughly vetting each nomination, they select only those they believe merit consideration for an award, placing the approved applicants on a comprehensive ballot that is sent to over 3,000 experienced senior business executives worldwide.\n\nThe Steering Committee is also responsible for selecting the [https://edisonawards.com/achievementaward.php Edison Achievement Award] recipient, selecting individuals who are on the cutting edge of innovation to receive this distinguished award.\n\n<br />\n==See also==\n\n* [[List of engineering awards]]\n\n<br />\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}<br />\n==External links==\n* [http://www.edisonawards.com/ Official Edison Awards website]\n*[https://edisonawards.com/downloads/EdisonAwards_overview.pdf Edison Awards Overview]\n*[https://edisonawards.com/downloads/EdisonAwards_snapshot.pdf Edison Awards Snapshot]\n\n[[Category:American awards]]\n[[Category:Engineering awards]]\n[[Category:Design awards]]\n[[Category:Business and industry awards]]\n", "name_user": "Sourdough.Startup", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding other Wikipedia award list sites to link to", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edison_Awards"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Netherlands", "text_new": "{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in the Netherlands}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Netherlands\n| map1            = COVID-19 pandemic in the Netherlands \u2013 registered infections by province from 21 to 31 March 2020.gif\n| legend1         = Numbers of registered infections per province from 21 to 31 March 2020\n| map2            = COVID-19 outbreak the Netherlands per capita cases map.svg\n| legend2         = Confirmed cases per 10,000 inhabitants by municipality\n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Netherlands]]\n| first_case      = <!-- Do not change Tilburg to Loon op Zand here. Although the first patient comes from Loon op Zand, he was diagnosed and hospitalised in Tilburg. --> [[Tilburg]]\n| arrival_date    = 27 February 2020<br/>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=02|day1=27|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = <!-- Do not fill in, at least not without consulting the talk page. -->\n| confirmed_cases = 23,097<ref name=\"rivm:total\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rivm.nl/en/news/current-information-about-novel-coronavirus-covid-19|title=Current information about the novel coronavirus (COVID-19)|website=rivm.nl|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n| recovery_cases  = <!-- Do not change as long as the authorities don't publish official numbers. --> unknown{{Efn|The Dutch Government agency RIVM, responsible for the constituent country the Netherlands, does not count its number of recoveries.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Coronavirus in the Netherlands: the questions you want answered |work=Dutch News |url= https://www.dutchnews.nl/news/2020/03/coronavirus-in-the-netherlands-the-questions-you-want-answered/ |date=12 March 2020}}</ref>|name=tn|group=}}\n| deaths          = 2,511<ref name=\"rivm:total\" />\n| total_ili       = \n| website         = \n}}\n\nThe [[2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have spread to the [[Netherlands]] on 27 February 2020, when its first COVID-19 case was confirmed in [[Tilburg]]. It involved a 56-year-old Dutchman who had arrived in the Netherlands from Italy. As of 10 April, there are 23,097 confirmed cases of infection and 2,511 deaths.<ref name=\"rivm:total\" /> The first death occurred on 6 March, when an 86-year-old patient died in [[Rotterdam]].<ref name=\"rivm:d1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rivm.nl/nieuws/patient-met-nieuw-coronavirus-overleden|title=Pati\u00ebnt met nieuw coronavirus overleden|date=6 March 2020|website=rivm.nl|language=nl|access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n__TOC__\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, who had initially come to the attention of the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=\"Elsevier\">{{cite web|url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center|last=Elsevier|date=|website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Reynolds4March2020\">{{Cite news|last=Reynolds|first=Matt|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic?|date=4 March 2020|work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|issn=1357-0978}}</ref>\n\nUnlike [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]], the [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 <ref name=\"Imperial13March2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus|website=Imperial News|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Gov.ukHCIDDef\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England|last=|first=|date=|website=GOV.UK|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> has been much lower, but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=\"WFSA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus|last=|first=|date=|website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Imperial13March2020\" />\n\n== Timeline ==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Netherlands medical cases chart}}\n\n===January 2020===\n* As of 22 January 2020, the main international airport [[Amsterdam Airport Schiphol|Schiphol]] was not taking extra measures against the spread of the virus, stating the lack of direct flights from or to Wuhan.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nu.nl/binnenland/6025578/schiphol-en-airlines-treffen-nog-geen-maatregelen-tegen-coronavirus.html|title=Schiphol en airlines treffen nog geen maatregelen tegen coronavirus|date=22 January 2020|website=Nu.nl|language=nl|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200123215656/https://www.nu.nl/binnenland/6025578/schiphol-en-airlines-treffen-nog-geen-maatregelen-tegen-coronavirus.html|archive-date=23 January 2020|access-date=22 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===February 2020===\n*26 February: the Dutch foreign ministry updated its travel advice for Italy, advising citizens not to travel to areas affected by the COVID-19 outbreak.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dutchnews.nl/news/2020/02/dutch-update-italy-travel-advice-as-coronavirus-takes-hold/|title=Dutch update Italy travel advice as coronavirus takes hold|date=25 February 2020|website=DutchNews.nl|access-date=27 February 2020}}</ref>\n*27 February: the first confirmed case of COVID-19, a man from [[Loon op Zand]] who had been in the [[Lombardy]] region of Italy was admitted to Elisabeth-TweeSteden Hospital in [[Tilburg]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rivm.nl/node/152811|title=Patient with novel coronavirus COVID-19 in the Netherlands|date=27 February 2020|website=rivm.nl|access-date=6 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"telegraaf:1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraaf.nl/nieuws/214089776/rivm-eerste-coronageval-in-nederland|title=RIVM: Eerste coronageval in Nederland|date=27 February 2020|website=De Telegraaf|language=nl|access-date=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n*28 February: a second case confirmed, a woman from Amsterdam who had visited the Lombardy region in Italy was in home isolation in [[Diemen]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rivm.nl/nieuws/tweede-patient-in-nederland-met-covid-19|title=Tweede patient in Nederland met COVID-19|date=28 February 2020|website=rivm.nl|language=nl|access-date=6 March 2020}}</ref> She is an employee of the [[Academic Medical Center]] in Amsterdam.<ref name=\":6\">{{cite web|url=https://nos.nl/l/2324942|title=Amsterdamse coronapati\u00ebnt werkt in Amsterdam UMC|website=nos.nl|language=nl|access-date=28 February 2020}}</ref>\n*29 February: third and fourth cases confirmed, the husband and the youngest child of the second case.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rivm.nl/nieuws/twee-contacten-testen-positief-voor-covid-19|title=Twee contacten testen positief voor COVID-19|date=29 February 2020|website=rivm.nl|language=nl|access-date=6 March 2020}}</ref> On the same day the wife and daughter of the first case were also confirmed to have the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rivm.nl/nieuws/ook-enkele-contacten-van-tilburgse-patient-testten-positief-voor-covid-19|title=Ook enkele contacten van Tilburgse pati\u00ebnt testten positief voor COVID-19|date=29 February 2020|website=rivm.nl|language=nl|access-date=6 March 2020}}</ref> Another case is a woman from [[Delft]] who is isolated at home.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rivm.nl/nieuws/patient-met-covid-19-in-delft|title=Pati\u00ebnt met COVID-19 in Delft|date=29 February 2020|website=rivm.nl|language=nl|access-date=6 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":9\">{{cite web |url=https://nos.nl/artikel/2325216-ook-vrouw-in-delft-heeft-corona-zevende-geval-in-nederland.html |title=Ook vrouw in Delft heeft corona, zevende geval in Nederland |website=NOS |language=Dutch |date=29 February 2020 |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===March 2020===\n====1\u201310 March====\n* 1 March: three new cases were confirmed: a 49-year-old woman from [[Nieuwendijk]] who had been hospitalised at [[Erasmus MC]] in [[Rotterdam]], a woman in Tilburg and a man in [[Dalen]], [[Coevorden]]. The 49-year-old woman had been admitted to the Beatrix Hospital in [[Gorinchem]] on 21 February before being transferred to Rotterdam later. She arrived at the Beatrix Hospital with respiratory problems and stayed in intensive care for a week. A test for [[SARS-CoV-2]] was not conducted since she had no connection to infected areas or people. Therefore, her infection went unnoticed for over a week. On 1 March it was announced that she had COVID-19 and that she had been relocated to Erasmus MC due to her deteriorating condition earlier. Since then the Beatrix Hospital went into lock-down out of precaution for a few days. Only personnel was allowed to enter and leave the building. The hospital fully reopened on 5 March, after all employees had tested negative.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rivm.nl/nieuws/drie-nieuwe-patienten-met-covid-19|title=Drie nieuwe pati\u00ebnten met COVID-19|date=1 March 2020|website=rivm.nl|language=nl|access-date=6 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nos.nl/artikel/2325309-beatrixziekenhuis-gorinchem-gesloten-om-coronavirus-tien-patienten-in-nl.html|title=Beatrixziekenhuis Gorinchem gesloten om coronavirus, tien pati\u00ebnten in NL|date=1 March 2020|website=nos.nl|language=nl|access-date=6 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.destadgorinchem.nl/lokaal/zorg/326154/beatrixziekenhuis-gorinchem-en-lingepolikliniek-leerdam-donderdag-weer-open-na-melding|title=Beatrixziekenhuis Gorinchem en Lingepolikliniek Leerdam donderdag weer open na melding coronavirus |website=DeStadGorinchem.nl |language=Dutch |date=4 March 2020 |accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n* 4 March: the total number of cases was 38, which included one person passing through the Netherlands who was isolated in [[Hoofddorp]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nos.nl/artikel/2325726-coronapatient-die-in-container-hoofddorp-zat-nu-naar-andere-locatie.html|title=Coronapati\u00ebnt die in container Hoofddorp zat nu naar andere locatie|date=4 March 2020|website=nos.nl|language=nl|access-date=4 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://nos.nl/artikel/2325850-ook-ziekenhuispersoneel-in-eindhoven-breda-en-den-bosch-besmet-met-corona.html|title=Ook ziekenhuispersoneel in Eindhoven, Breda en Den Bosch besmet met corona|website=nos.nl|language=nl|date=5 March 2020|access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref> The next day this number more than doubled to 82. According to [[Bruno Bruins]], Dutch minister for Medical Care, this was due to a catch-up in conducted tests.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ad.nl/binnenland/aantal-coronapatienten-in-nederland-ruim-verdubbeld-naar-82~a886fdb8/|title=Aantal coronapati\u00ebnten in Nederland ruim verdubbeld naar 82|date=5 March 2020|website=Algemeen Dagblad|language=nl|access-date=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n* 6 March: the [[Netherlands National Institute for Public Health and the Environment|RIVM]] announced the first death due to COVID-19, an 86-year-old patient.<ref name=\"rivm:d1\" /><ref name=\":20200306a\">{{cite web|url=https://nltimes.nl/2020/03/06/first-coronavirus-fatality-netherlands-rotterdam-patient-dead-86|title=First coronavirus fatality in Netherlands: Rotterdam patient dead at 86|website=nltimes.nl|date=6 March 2020|access-date=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n* 9 March: the total number of cases was 321, of which more than one-third were found in North Brabant.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nu.nl/coronavirus/6036103/aantal-met-coronavirus-besmette-personen-in-nederland-stijgt-naar-321.html|title=Aantal met coronavirus besmette personen in Nederland stijgt naar 321|date=9 March 2020|website=nu.nl|language=nl|access-date=9 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.noordhollandsdagblad.nl/cnt/dmf20200309_90236518/geen-nieuwe-besmettingen-met-coronavirus-in-gooi-en-vechtstreek-aantal-zieken-blijft-op-22|title=Geen nieuwe besmettingen met coronavirus in Gooi, Vechtstreek en Eemland; aantal zieken blijft op 22|date=9 March 2020|website=noordhollandsdagblad.nl|language=nl|access-date=9 March 2020}}</ref> The prime minister [[Mark Rutte]] asked citizens to stop shaking hands and asked people in North Brabant to work from home if possible.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nos.nl/video/2326490-rutte-stop-met-handen-schudden-en-werk-thuis.html|date=9 March 2020|website=nos.nl|language=nl|title=Rutte: stop met handen schudden en werk thuis}}</ref>\n*10 March: stricter measures were introduced in the province of [[North Brabant]]. Larger events were banned, including professional football, a number of dance festivals, carnival parades and concerts. A scholarship program was cancelled at the [[Eindhoven University of Technology|University of Eindhoven]]. In addition to this, the mayor of [[Tilburg]] Theo Weterings called to limit social contacts for a week.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nrc.nl/nieuws/2020/03/10/coronablog-10-maart-a3993219|title=Brabant scherpt maatregelen rondom coronavirus aan|website=NRC|language=nl|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====11\u201320 March====\n*12 March: the government announced new measures that will be in effect through the end of the month. All events (concerts, sports) and all meetings with more than 100 people are now forbidden and the RIVM is encouraging people to work from home. The restriction also applies to museums. All Dutch universities will suspend physical teaching until 1 April, but online teaching will continue. Schools remain open.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nos.nl/liveblog/2326799-persconferentie-rutte-na-crisisoverleg-111-nieuwe-patienten-in-nederland.html|title=Events with 100+ visitors forbidden, cabinet calls for working from home}}</ref>\n*13 March, the government cancelled all flights from China, Iran, Italy, and South Korea, the countries with the highest number of coronavirus cases, for two weeks. Flights leaving the destinations before 18:00 on that day could still land in the Netherlands.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nu.nl/coronavirus/6037229/kabinet-schrapt-vluchten-uit-china-italie-iran-en-zuid-korea.html|title=Kabinet schrapt vluchten uit China, Itali\u00eb, Iran en Zuid-Korea|date=13 March 2020|work=[[nu.nl]]|language=Dutch}}</ref>\n* 15 March: the total number of cases was 1,135. The Public Health Service (GGD) estimated that as of this day, 6,000 people in the Netherlands had been infected. This is because since 12 March people with mild complaints had not been tested any more.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nos.nl/artikel/2327182-acht-nieuwe-coronadoden-162-mensen-opgenomen-in-ziekenhuis.html|title=Acht nieuwe coronadoden, 162 mensen opgenomen in ziekenhuis|date=15 March 2020|website=nos.nl|language=nl|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref> Public measures were also tightened up. Schools and childcare centres will remain closed until 6 April, as well as caf\u00e9s, restaurants, sports clubs, saunas, sex clubs and [[Coffeeshop (Netherlands)|coffeeshops]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://nos.nl/artikel/2327194-alle-scholen-en-horeca-tot-6-april-dicht-in-strijd-tegen-coronavirus.html|title=Alle scholen, caf\u00e9s en restaurants tot en met 6 april dicht om coronavirus|date=15 March 2020|work=NOS|language=Dutch|access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n* 16 March: In the evening Prime Minister [[Mark Rutte]] addressed the nation about the coronavirus. It was the first time a prime minister had addressed the nation since the [[1973 oil crisis]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.volkskrant.nl/gs-bea83379|title=Live toespraak van Rutte is een absolute zeldzaamheid|last=Bekkum|first=Dylan van|date=16 March 2020|website=de Volkskrant|language=nl-NL|access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref> In his speech he announced that the government chooses not to resort to population confinement measures, but to rely on the measures taken earlier in order to try to assert maximum control over the spread of the virus. Reasoning that the virus is here to stay, the preferred approach would be to tackle the epidemic by building [[herd immunity|population immunity]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.government.nl/documents/speeches/2020/03/16/television-address-by-prime-minister-mark-rutte-of-the-netherlands |title= Television address by Prime Minister Mark Rutte of the Netherlands |date= 16 March 2020 |website= government.nl |access-date= 31 March 2020}}</ref>\n* 17 March: the total number of confirmed cases was 1,705, of which 314 patients had been admitted to the hospital.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nu.nl/coronavirus/6038155/19-nieuwe-sterfgevallen-in-nederland-bevestigde-besmettingen-naar-1705.html|title=19 nieuwe sterfgevallen in Nederland, bevestigde besmettingen naar 1.705|date=17 March 2020|website=nu.nl|language=nl|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"rivm:total\" /> [[Arie Slob]] notified that schools could stay open for the sole purpose of letting final exam candidates finish their last schoolwork. Schools will only open if certain conditions are met. This measure is taken to ensure that final exam candidates are prepared for the national exam at the start of May.\n*18 March: the Dutch minister for Medical care, Bruno Bruins became unwell during a debate and collapsed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nos.nl/l/2327555|title='Oververmoeide' minister Bruins zakt in elkaar tijdens coronadebat|website=nos.nl|language=nl|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> On 19 March he resigned from his position as minister for Medical care. In a press conference it was announced that [[Hugo de Jonge]] would from then on handle the Coronavirus pandemic in the Netherlands.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.trouw.nl/gs-b450b28d|title=Oververmoeide minister Bruno Bruins treedt af|last=Hommes|first=Kick|date=19 March 2020|website=Trouw|language=nl-NL|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n*19 March: A traveller from the Netherlands was described as \"Patient Zero of the Winelands\" in South Africa.<ref>\n{{cite web |url=https://www.dispatchlive.co.za/news/2020-03-17-patient-zero-of-the-winelands-cape-estates-close-over-coronavirus/ |title='Patient Zero of the winelands': Cape estates close over coronavirus |last=Knowler |first=Wendy |work=DispatchLive.co.za |date=17 March 2020 |access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n*20 March: in a press conference it was announced that [[Martin van Rijn]] will become the new minister for Medical care.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nos.nl/l/2327735|title=PvdA'er Martin van Rijn nieuwe minister voor Medische Zorg|website=nos.nl|language=nl|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> In the evening, King of the Netherlands [[Willem-Alexander of the Netherlands|Willem-Alexander]] addressed the nation, due to the coronavirus outbreak.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nos.nl/l/2327794|title=Koning: coronavirus kunnen we niet stoppen, eenzaamheidsvirus wel|website=nos.nl|language=nl|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====21\u201331 March====\n*22 March: [[NOC*NSF]] (Dutch Olympic Committee*Dutch Sports Federation) sent a letter to the [[IOC]]. It states the advice that the [[2020 Summer Olympics]] only can take place when the coronavirus crisis is under control worldwide.<ref>https://nocnsf.nl/media/2511/brief-nocnsf-aan-ioc_os-tokyo-2020.pdf</ref> The NOC also asked for more certainty for the athletes. The letter was supported by most of the National Sport Federations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ad.nl/olympische-spelen/meeste-sportbonden-steunen-brief-noc-nsf-aan-ioc~a4ab3429/|title=Meeste sportbonden steunen brief NOC*NSF aan IOC|website=Algemeen Dagblad|date=23 March 2020|language=NL}}</ref>\n*23 March: stricter social distancing rules were announced in a press conference.<ref name=\"social distancing\">{{cite web|url=https://www.volkskrant.nl/gs-b2ea8620|title=Geen Koningsdag en eredivisie, forse boetes en strenge handhaving|last=Mis\u00e9rus|first=Mark|last2=Dirks|first2=Bart|date=23 March 2020|website=de Volkskrant|language=nl-NL|access-date=24 March 2020|last3=Kreling|first3=Tom}}</ref>\n*24 March: in a press conference, the Dutch [[Ministry of Education, Culture and Science (Netherlands)|Minister for Primary and Secondary Education]] announced all [[Eindexamen|final examinations]] (centraal eindexamen) for secondary education were cancelled.<ref name=\"exam cancellations\">{{cite web|url=https://nos.nl/l/2328153|title=Centrale eindexamens middelbare scholieren gaan niet door|website=nos.nl|language=nl|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n*26 March: [[NOC*NSF]] (Dutch Olympic Committee*Dutch Sports Federation) provided hundreds of cooling vests for healthcare personnel at the intensive care departments in several hospitals. Doctors have to work in warm conditions among others due to the protective clothing they have to wear. The vests would initially be used by the Dutch athletes at the 2020 Summer Olympics.<ref name=20200327nos1>{{cite web|url=https://nos.nl/artikel/2328462-koelvesten-voor-ic-medewerkers-beschikbaar-gesteld-het-is-net-topsport.html|language=NL|title=Koelvesten voor IC-medewerkers beschikbaar gesteld: 'Het is net topsport'|website=nos.nl|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n*29 March: The total number of positive coronavirus cases in the country surpassed 10,000. Upon the announcement, RIVM stated that 'the number of hospitalised patients and the number of deaths are increasing less quickly than would have been expected without measures'. It further said that since testing was done mostly only for the very sick and healthcare workers, the actual number of infections is likely to be far higher.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nationalpost.com/pmn/health-pmn/dutch-coronavirus-cases-pass-10000-health-authorities|title=Dutch coronavirus cases pass 10,000 -health authorities|website=National Post|date=29 March 2020|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n*31 March: In a press conference it was announced that all measures initiated on 15 March will be extended until 28 April.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nos.nl/l/2328969|title=Kabinet verlengt maatregelen tegen corona tot en met 28 april|website=nos.nl|language=nl|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====April====\n{{empty section|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Prevention measures and response==\n{{Expand section|date=March 2020}}\nIn late March, the government announced strict social distancing rules as cases surged over 5,000. All events and gatherings of three people or more (that are not from the same household) are banned until 1 June. Furthermore, in public space a distance of at least 1.5 meters between people not from the same household must be observed, and stores and other venues are to enforce this distancing among their visitors. Fines will be issued to those not complying with the new rules. Companies may face a fine up to \u20ac4,000, individuals risk a fine up to \u20ac400. Prime Minister [[Mark Rutte]] repeated his call to keep distance from each other.<ref name=\"social distancing\"/>\nFinal examinations of secondary school were cancelled on 24 March.<ref name=\"exam cancellations\"/>\n\n===Testing===\n{{Expand section|date=March 2020}}\nBy mid-March, the country could test about 1,000 samples per day, which is less than the capabilities of other European countries.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Newmark |first1=Zack |title=Coronavirus cases surge to 3,631 as 30 more Dutch patients die |url=https://nltimes.nl/2020/03/21/coronavirus-cases-surge-3631-30-dutch-patients-die |work=NL Times |date=21 March 2020}}</ref> This also explains a relatively large ratio of the number of deaths to the number of confirmed cases.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Waster |first1=Jeroen |title=Groeiende kritiek experts op gebrek aan testen in Nederland |url=https://www.nrc.nl/nieuws/2020/03/20/groeiende-kritiek-experts-op-gebrek-aan-testen-in-nederland-a3994452 |date=20 March 2020 |language=Dutch}}</ref> As of 25 March, 2,500 samples have been tested daily and a total number of 38,000 tests performed. Because of the limited availability of testing capacity, certain groups were prioritised in testing, such as healthcare workers, elderly, and people with acute symptoms.<ref>{{cite news |title=RIVM: verspreiding coronavirus lijkt af te remmen |url=https://www.rtlnieuws.nl/nieuws/nederland/artikel/5069046/coronavirus-jaap-van-dissel-rivm |work=RTL Nieuws |date=25 March 2020}}</ref> A lack of testing capacity causes a distinct number of deaths by COVID-19 that are not registered as such, although local doctors can recognise the symptoms.<ref>{{cite news |title=Huisartsen: 'Niet geteste pati\u00ebnten die overlijden aan corona ontbreken in sterftecijfer RIVM' |url=https://www.bnnvara.nl/zembla/artikelen/huisartsen-niet-geteste-patinten-die-overlijden-aan-corona-ontbreken-in-sterftecijfer-rivm |work=Zembla |date=26 March 2020}}</ref> By the end of March, the country was testing about 4,000 people per day, with the goal of expanding the testing capacity to about 17,500 daily tests in a couple of weeks. Once such a testing capacity has been reached the Dutch government wants to expand its testing capacity to 29,000 tests a day.<ref>{{cite news |title=Aantal coronatests komende weken verviervoudigd |url=https://www.rtlnieuws.nl/nieuws/politiek/artikel/5076451/aantal-coronatests-wordt-verviervoudigd-rivm-corona-kabinet |work=RTL Times |language=Dutch |date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Impact==\n{{Expand section|date=March 2020}}\n[[File:Empty chips shelves in AH Delft 02.jpg|thumb|Empty shelves in a supermarket in [[Delft]] as a result of [[hoarding]], 15 March]]\nIn response to regulations announced on 12 March, [[panic buying]] of food, toilet paper and medicines, resulted in empty shelves in supermarkets. Prime Minister [[Mark Rutte]] appealed to the nation to stop this behaviour.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nu.nl/coronavirus/6037314/rutte-doet-oproep-stop-met-hamsteren.html|title=Rutte doet oproep: Stop met hamsteren|date=13 March 2020|work=[[nu.nl]]|language=Dutch}}</ref> On 12 March it was announced that all public events with more than 100 people will be cancelled until 6 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rijksoverheid.nl/actueel/nieuws/2020/03/12/nieuwe-maatregelen-tegen-verspreiding-coronavirus-in-nederland|title=Nieuwe maatregelen tegen verspreiding coronavirus in Nederland \u2013 Nieuwsbericht \u2013 Rijksoverheid.nl|date=12 March 2020}}</ref> On 24 March this period was extended to 1 June for all permit-requiring events.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.volkskrant.nl/gs-b7664a68|title=Waarom 1 juni en nog 10 vragen over de nieuwe crisismaatregelen|last=Mebius|first=Dion|date=24 March 2020|website=de Volkskrant|language=nl-NL|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> Three days later it was announced in a press conference that all restaurants, museums, sport clubs and schools had to close.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Economy ===\nOn 26 March, the [[Bureau for Economic Policy Analysis]] published the first calculations of the economic expectations. These expectations are based on the length of the prevention measures against the coronavirus pandemic. If these measures are present for three months, the Dutch economy is expected to shrink by 1.2 percent in 2020. If these measures are required for a year the economy would decline with 10 percent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nos.nl/l/2328385|title=CPB vreest diepe recessie, economie kan krimpen met 7,7 procent|website=nos.nl|language=nl|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref> In all cases it is expected that the economy will slightly grow the following year.\n\n==Statistics==\n{{See also|Template:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Netherlands medical cases|label 1=Daily coronavirus cases by province in the Netherlands}}\n\n[[File:COVID19-30032020-Netherlands_GGD.png|thumb|Public Health Service (GGD) districts by number of COVID-19 infections (updated: 30 March)<ref name=\"rivm:total\" />]]\n[[File:COVID19-Netherlands-InfDat2.png|thumb|Public Health Service (GGD) districts by date of first COVID-19 infection<ref name=\"rivm:total\" />]]\n[[File:CoViD-19 NL.svg|thumb|Number of cases (blue) and number of deaths (red) on a [[logarithmic scale]].]]\n\n<!-- Do not update the chart until the authorities have released the final figures at the set time (14:00) daily for consistency and reliability purposes. -->\n<div class=\"toccolours\" style=\"display:inline-block; width:700px; margin:1em 0;\"><center>'''Total confirmed cases, hospitalisations and deaths'''</center>\n{{GraphChart\n|type=line\n|linewidth=2\n|showSymbols=1\n|width=600\n|colors={{Medical cases chart/Bar colors|3}}, RoyalBlue, {{Medical cases chart/Bar colors|1}}\n|showValu