ebSite_rapport_20200408_1036%20%281%29.pdf|title=Epidemiologische situatie COVID-19 in Nederland. Rijksinstituut voor Volksgezondheid en Milieu - RIVM. 08 april 2020, 10:00|date=8 April 2020|website=rivm.nl|language=nl|access-date=8 April 2020|layurl=https://www.rivm.nl/documenten/epidemiologische-situatie-covid-19-in-nederland-8-april-2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n{{col-break}}\n\n{{col-end}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n{{noteFoot}}\n\n==See also== \n{{cols}}\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe]]\n* [[2019-2020 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory]]\n{{colend}}\n\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|Netherlands|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.rivm.nl/en RIVM]\n* Data and maps, frequently updated:\n** {{cite web |url=https://coronavirus-global.com/netherlands |title=Coronavirus Netherlands updates and news |trans-title=Latest news and statistics of coronavirus in Netherlands. |access-date=4 April 2020 |language=English, French, Spanish, Portuguese, German, Italian, Swedish, Norwegian, Finnish, Estonian, Russian}}\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Netherlands| ]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Netherlands]]\n[[Category:2020 in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe|Netherlands]]\n", "name_user": "Thayts", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eStatistics", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_the_Netherlands"}
{"title_page": "Biomolecular complex", "text_new": "{{merge|Macromolecular assembly|discuss=Talk:Macromolecular assembly#Merger proposal|date=October 2019}}\n'''Biomolecular complex''', also called '''macromolecular complex''' or '''biomacromolecular complex''', is any biological complex made of more than one [[biopolymer]] ([[protein]], [[RNA]], [[DNA]],\n<ref name=biomolecular_complex_protein_DNA_RNA__2005>{{Cite journal\n| doi = 10.1093/nar/gki369\n| issn = 0305-1048\n| volume = 33\n| issue = suppl 2\n| pages = W342\u2013W346\n| last = Kleinjung\n| first = Jens\n|author2=Franca Fraternali\n| title = POPSCOMP: an automated interaction analysis of biomolecular complexes\n| journal = [[Nucleic Acids Research]]\n| accessdate = 2013-11-14\n| date = 2005-07-01\n| url = http://nar.oxfordjournals.org/content/33/suppl_2/W342\n| pmid=15980485\n| pmc=1160130\n}}</ref>\n[[carbohydrate]]) or large non-polymeric biomolecules ([[lipid]]). The interactions between these biomolecules are non-covalent.\n<ref name=Ribosome_macromolecular_device_2012_REVIEW>{{Cite journal\n| doi = 10.1146/annurev-biophys-050511-102314\n| volume = 41\n| issue = 1\n| pages = 1\u201319\n| last = Moore\n| first = Peter B.\n| title = How Should We Think About the Ribosome?\n| journal = [[Annual Review of Biophysics]]\n| date = 2012\n| pmid = 22577819\n}}</ref>\nExamples:\n* [[Protein complex]]es, some of which are [[multienzyme complex]]es: [[proteasome]], [[DNA polymerase III holoenzyme]], [[RNA polymerase II holoenzyme]], symmetric viral [[capsid]]s, chaperonin complex [[GroEL]]-[[GroES]], [[photosystem I]], [[ATP synthase]], [[ferritin]].\n* RNA-protein complexes: [[ribosome]], [[spliceosome]], [[vault (organelle)|vault]], [[SnRNP]]. Such complexes in cell nucleus are called [[ribonucleoprotein]]s (RNPs).\n* DNA-protein complexes: [[nucleosome]].\n* Protein-lipid complexes: [[lipoprotein]].<ref name=Trends_in_biochemical_sciences_2015>\n{{Cite journal|\ndoi = 10.1016/j.tibs.2015.11.006|\npmid = 26699226|\nvolume = 41|\nissue = 1|\npages = 1\u20133|\nlast = Neuman|\nfirst = Nicole|\ntitle = The Complex Macromolecular Complex: Trends in Biochemical Sciences|\njournal = Trends in Biochemical Sciences|\naccessdate = 2018-07-11|\nurl = https://www.cell.com/trends/biochemical-sciences/fulltext/S0968-0004(15)00228-5|\ndate = January 2016}}</ref><ref name=Structure_2005>\n{{Cite journal|\ndoi = 10.1016/j.str.2005.01.008|\npmid = 15766539|\nissn = 0969-2126|\nvolume = 13|\nissue = 3|\npages = 381\u2013388|\nlast1 = Dutta|\nfirst1 = Shuchismita|\nlast2 = Berman|\nfirst2 = Helen M.|\ntitle = Large Macromolecular Complexes in the Protein Data Bank: A Status Report|\njournal = Structure|\ndate = 2005-03-01}}</ref>\n\nThe biomacromolecular complexes are studied structurally by [[X-ray crystallography]], [[Nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy of proteins|NMR spectroscopy of proteins]], [[cryo-electron microscopy]] and successive [[single particle analysis]], and [[electron tomography]].\n<ref>{{Cite journal\n| doi = 10.1016/j.sbi.2004.04.006\n| pmid = 15193311\n| issn = 0959-440X\n| volume = 14\n| issue = 3\n| pages = 313\u2013324\n| last = Russell\n| first = Robert B\n|author2=Frank Alber |author3=Patrick Aloy |author4=Fred P Davis |author5=Dmitry Korkin |author6=Matthieu Pichaud |author7=Maya Topf |author8=Andrej Sali\n | title = A structural perspective on protein\u2013protein interactions\n| journal = [[Current Opinion in Structural Biology]]\n| date = June 2004\n}}</ref>\nThe atomic structure models obtained by X-ray crystallography and biomolecular NMR spectroscopy can be [[Macromolecular docking|docked]] into the much larger structures of biomolecular complexes obtained by lower resolution techniques like electron microscopy, electron tomography, and [[small-angle X-ray scattering]].\n<ref>{{Cite journal\n| doi = 10.1111/j.1742-4658.2004.04473.x\n| pmid = 15654870\n| issn = 1742-4658\n| volume = 272\n| issue = 2\n| pages = 293\u2013312\n| last = van Dijk\n| first = Aalt D. J. |author2=Rolf Boelens |author3=Alexandre M. J. J. Bonvin\n| title = Data-driven docking for the study of biomolecular complexes\n| journal = [[FEBS Journal]]\n| year = 2005\n| hdl = 1874/336958\n}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Quaternary structure]]\n* [[Multiprotein complex]]\n* [[Macromolecular assembly]]: macromolecular assembly in biology is the same as biomacromolecular complex.\n* [[Organelle]]: the broadest definition of \"organelle\" includes not only membrane bound cellular structures, but also very large biomolecular complexes.\n* [[Multi-state modeling of biomolecules]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{aut|Berg, J.}} {{aut|Tymoczko, J.}} and {{aut|Stryer, L.}}, ''Biochemistry.'' (W. H. Freeman and Company, 2002), {{ISBN|0-7167-4955-6}}\n* {{aut|Cox, M.}} and {{aut|Nelson, D. L.}}, ''Lehninger Principles of Biochemistry.'' (Palgrave Macmillan, 2004), {{ISBN|0-7167-4339-6}}\n\n{{Biological organisation}} \n\n[[Category:Protein complexes]]\n[[Category:RNA]]\n[[Category:Structural biology]]\n[[Category:Molecular biology]]\n[[Category:Cell biology]]\n", "text_old": "{{merge|Macromolecular assembly|discuss=Talk:Macromolecular assembly#Merger proposal|date=October 2019}}\n'''Biomolecular complex''', also called '''macromolecular complex''' or '''biomacromolecular complex''', is any biological complex made of more than one molecule of [[protein]], [[RNA]], [[DNA]],\n<ref name=biomolecular_complex_protein_DNA_RNA__2005>{{Cite journal\n| doi = 10.1093/nar/gki369\n| issn = 0305-1048\n| volume = 33\n| issue = suppl 2\n| pages = W342\u2013W346\n| last = Kleinjung\n| first = Jens\n|author2=Franca Fraternali\n| title = POPSCOMP: an automated interaction analysis of biomolecular complexes\n| journal = [[Nucleic Acids Research]]\n| accessdate = 2013-11-14\n| date = 2005-07-01\n| url = http://nar.oxfordjournals.org/content/33/suppl_2/W342\n| pmid=15980485\n| pmc=1160130\n}}</ref>\n[[lipid]]s, or [[carbohydrate]]s. The interactions between these biomolecules are non-covalent.\n<ref name=Ribosome_macromolecular_device_2012_REVIEW>{{Cite journal\n| doi = 10.1146/annurev-biophys-050511-102314\n| volume = 41\n| issue = 1\n| pages = 1\u201319\n| last = Moore\n| first = Peter B.\n| title = How Should We Think About the Ribosome?\n| journal = [[Annual Review of Biophysics]]\n| date = 2012\n| pmid = 22577819\n}}</ref>\nExamples:\n* [[Protein complex]]es, some of which are [[multienzyme complex]]es: [[proteasome]], [[DNA polymerase III holoenzyme]], [[RNA polymerase II holoenzyme]], symmetric viral [[capsid]]s, chaperonin complex [[GroEL]]-[[GroES]], [[photosystem I]], [[ATP synthase]], [[ferritin]].\n* RNA-protein complexes: [[ribosome]], [[spliceosome]], [[vault (organelle)|vault]], [[SnRNP]]. Such complexes in cell nucleus are called [[ribonucleoprotein]]s (RNPs).\n* DNA-protein complexes: [[nucleosome]].\n* Protein-lipid complexes: [[lipoprotein]].<ref name=Trends_in_biochemical_sciences_2015>\n{{Cite journal|\ndoi = 10.1016/j.tibs.2015.11.006|\npmid = 26699226|\nvolume = 41|\nissue = 1|\npages = 1\u20133|\nlast = Neuman|\nfirst = Nicole|\ntitle = The Complex Macromolecular Complex: Trends in Biochemical Sciences|\njournal = Trends in Biochemical Sciences|\naccessdate = 2018-07-11|\nurl = https://www.cell.com/trends/biochemical-sciences/fulltext/S0968-0004(15)00228-5|\ndate = January 2016}}</ref><ref name=Structure_2005>\n{{Cite journal|\ndoi = 10.1016/j.str.2005.01.008|\npmid = 15766539|\nissn = 0969-2126|\nvolume = 13|\nissue = 3|\npages = 381\u2013388|\nlast1 = Dutta|\nfirst1 = Shuchismita|\nlast2 = Berman|\nfirst2 = Helen M.|\ntitle = Large Macromolecular Complexes in the Protein Data Bank: A Status Report|\njournal = Structure|\ndate = 2005-03-01}}</ref>\n\nThe biomacromolecular complexes are studied structurally by [[X-ray crystallography]], [[Nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy of proteins|NMR spectroscopy of proteins]], [[cryo-electron microscopy]] and successive [[single particle analysis]], and [[electron tomography]].\n<ref>{{Cite journal\n| doi = 10.1016/j.sbi.2004.04.006\n| pmid = 15193311\n| issn = 0959-440X\n| volume = 14\n| issue = 3\n| pages = 313\u2013324\n| last = Russell\n| first = Robert B\n|author2=Frank Alber |author3=Patrick Aloy |author4=Fred P Davis |author5=Dmitry Korkin |author6=Matthieu Pichaud |author7=Maya Topf |author8=Andrej Sali\n | title = A structural perspective on protein\u2013protein interactions\n| journal = [[Current Opinion in Structural Biology]]\n| date = June 2004\n}}</ref>\nThe atomic structure models obtained by X-ray crystallography and biomolecular NMR spectroscopy can be [[Macromolecular docking|docked]] into the much larger structures of biomolecular complexes obtained by lower resolution techniques like electron microscopy, electron tomography, and [[small-angle X-ray scattering]].\n<ref>{{Cite journal\n| doi = 10.1111/j.1742-4658.2004.04473.x\n| pmid = 15654870\n| issn = 1742-4658\n| volume = 272\n| issue = 2\n| pages = 293\u2013312\n| last = van Dijk\n| first = Aalt D. J. |author2=Rolf Boelens |author3=Alexandre M. J. J. Bonvin\n| title = Data-driven docking for the study of biomolecular complexes\n| journal = [[FEBS Journal]]\n| year = 2005\n| hdl = 1874/336958\n}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Quaternary structure]]\n* [[Multiprotein complex]]\n* [[Macromolecular assembly]]: macromolecular assembly in biology is the same as biomacromolecular complex.\n* [[Organelle]]: the broadest definition of \"organelle\" includes not only membrane bound cellular structures, but also very large biomolecular complexes.\n* [[Multi-state modeling of biomolecules]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{aut|Berg, J.}} {{aut|Tymoczko, J.}} and {{aut|Stryer, L.}}, ''Biochemistry.'' (W. H. Freeman and Company, 2002), {{ISBN|0-7167-4955-6}}\n* {{aut|Cox, M.}} and {{aut|Nelson, D. L.}}, ''Lehninger Principles of Biochemistry.'' (Palgrave Macmillan, 2004), {{ISBN|0-7167-4339-6}}\n\n{{Biological organisation}} \n\n[[Category:Protein complexes]]\n[[Category:RNA]]\n[[Category:Structural biology]]\n[[Category:Molecular biology]]\n[[Category:Cell biology]]\n", "name_user": "Kazkaskazkasako", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biomolecular_complex"}
{"title_page": "100 yen coin", "text_new": "{{about|the current 100 yen coin|the former 100 yen banknote|100 yen note}}\n\n{{Infobox Coin\n| Country = Japan\n| Denomination = One hundred yen\n| Value = 100\n| Unit = [[Japanese yen]]\n| Mass = 4.8\n| Diameter = 22.6\n| Thickness =\n| Edge = \n| Shape = circular\n| Center Hole Diameter = \n| Orientation = \n| Composition = [[Copper]] 75%, [[Nickel]] 25%\n| Years of Minting = 1957&ndash;present\n| Catalog Number = \n| Obverse = 100 Yen R\u00fcckseite.jpg\n| Obverse Design = [[Sakura]] blossoms\n| Obverse Designer = \n| Obverse Design Date = 1967\n| Reverse = 100 Yen Vorderseite.jpg\n| Reverse Design = \"100\" in Arabic numerals\n| Reverse Designer = \n| Reverse Design Date = 1967\n}}\n\nThe {{nihongo|'''100 yen coin'''|\u767e\u5186\u786c\u8ca8|Hyaku-en k\u014dka}} is a denomination of Japanese [[yen]]. The current design was first minted in silver in 1959 and saw a change of metal in 1967.<ref name=\"Mint\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mint.go.jp/eng/operations/coin/index.html |title=Operations Coins Currently Minted: Japan Mint |publisher=Japan Mint |accessdate=20 July 2010 |url-status=dead  |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091018050642/http://www.mint.go.jp/eng/operations/coin/index.html |archivedate=18 October 2009 |df= }}</ref> It is the second-highest denomination coin in Japan after the [[500 yen coin]]. The current 100 yen coin is one of two denominations which depict the emperor's rule date in Arabic numerals rather than Kanji. These numbers go from \"\u662d\u548c42\" [[Hirohito|Sh\u014dwa]], 42nd year of reign (1967) to \"\u4ee4\u548c2\" [[Naruhito|Reiwa]], 2nd year of reign (2020).\n\n==History==\n===Silver yen===\n100 yen coinage was first authorized in 1951 with the specification that the coins be made of a silver alloy.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qa8kAQAAMAAJ&q=100+yen+coinage+authorized&dq=100+yen+coinage+authorized&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&ppis=_e&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi3zIHFitzoAhVOj3IEHRkTCcgQ6AEwAnoECAgQAg&authuser=1|title=Engineering and Mining Journal|publisher=Western & Company|volume=168|issue=1-6|year=1967|page=104}}</ref> The first coins were minted for circulation in 1957 which featured a [[Fenghuang|phoenix]] on the reverse. The alloy decided upon consisted of 60% silver, 30% copper, and 10% zinc and came at a time when banknotes of the [[100 yen note|same denomination]] were already in circulation.<ref name=\"circulation\"/> The \"100 yen\" bill hence became a substitute to the coin as the two were allowed to co-circulate.<ref name=\"1964 Olympics\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AnIvbVsrlKUC&pg=PA16556&dq=100+yen+coin+1957&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&ppis=_e&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjwgaO4iNzoAhW6mHIEHa8tABwQ6AEwA3oECAEQAg&authuser=1#v=onepage&q=100%20yen%20coin%201957&f=false|title=Congressional Record is the official record of the proceedings and debates of the United States Congress|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|year=1965|volume=111|page=16556}}</ref> The design of the coin was changed in 1959 which removed Latin script (\"Yen\"), and changed the reverse side to show a sheaf of rice. To commemorate the summer [[1964 Summer Olympics|1964 Olympics]] in Tokyo 16 million ounces of silver was used to strike the 80,000,000 coins produced. None of these coins were recorded as ever going into circulation as they were grabbed and stored away as collectors items.<ref name=\"1964 Olympics\"/> The usage of silver worldwide for coinage was about to take a turn though, as the price of the bullion increased dramatically. The Japanese government had planned on producing 800 million silver coins over a 10 year span{{efn|Post-1964}}, but the amount of silver held was insufficient.<ref name=\"bonanza\">{{cite book|title=The History and Collection Guide of the New Revised Currency Notebook and Japanese Coins|author=Reishi Aoyama|publisher=Bonanza|year=1982}}</ref> Silver was dropped from the coinage in 1967, which led to coin hoarding and silver smuggling outside of the country for melting.<ref name=\"SI\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xLVdDgAAQBAJ&pg=PA75&dq=100+yen+coin+1957&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&ppis=_e&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjwgaO4iNzoAhW6mHIEHa8tABwQ6AEwAHoECAQQAg&authuser=1#v=onepage&q=100%20yen%20coin%201957&f=false|title=History of Digital Games: Developments in Art, Design and Interaction|author=Andrew Williams|publisher=CRC Press|year=2017|page=75}}</ref>\n\n===Cupronickel yen===\nThe new and current design of the 100 yen coin debuted in 1967, and features [[Prunus serrulata|sakura]] blossoms and the denomination in Japanese. A new alloy of 75% copper and 25% nickel ([[cupronickel]]) was decided upon to replace the former silver alloy. It was reported that by 1969 the monetary value in the old silver coins was $3 (USD) an ounce, prompting a \"coin retirement\" plan by the government.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZM_iAAAAMAAJ&q=100+yen+coin+1957&dq=100+yen+coin+1957&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&ppis=_e&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjwgaO4iNzoAhW6mHIEHa8tABwQ6AEwBXoECAkQAg&authuser=1|title=Economic Analysis of the Silver Industry|publisher=National Technical Information Service|year=1969|page=6-19}}</ref> On August 1, 1974 one hundred yen notes were withdrawn from circulation, but post [[World War II]] dated notes were allowed to retain their legal tender status.<ref name=\"NPB\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npb.go.jp/en/intro/kihon/kako/index.html|title=Banknotes in Use but No Longer Issued|publisher=[[National Printing Bureau]]|accessdate=September 2, 2019}}</ref> The amount of coins produced then decreased from the mid to late 1970's as a possible attempt to control economic inflation.<ref name=\"SI\"/> The issuance of the new 100 yen coin has also been cited as a factor in the rapid spread of [[vending machine]]s during this decade.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://warp.da.ndl.go.jp/info:ndljp/pid/9990748/www5.cao.go.jp/seikatsu/whitepaper/h2/wp-pl90-02102.html#sb2.1.2.10 |title=\u5e73\u62102\u5e74 \u56fd\u6c11\u751f\u6d3b\u767d\u66f8 \u7b2cII\u90e8 \u6280\u8853\u3068\u751f\u6d3b \u7b2c1\u7ae0 \u7b2c2\u7bc0 (10)|publisher=Economic Planning Agency|website=[[Cabinet Office (Japan)|Cabinet Office]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> By the late 1970's into the early 1980's a myth was established that tied the amount of coins produced with the growing popularity of the [[arcade game]] industry. While there were reports of Japanese cities briefly running out of 100 yen coins, arcade operators would have emptied out their machines and taken the money back to the bank.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p5PHDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA61&dq=100+yen+coin+early+1980s&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&ppis=_e&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwigp5Hc0dzoAhV6lnIEHWEjDzkQ6AEwA3oECAAQAg&authuser=1#v=onepage&q=needed%20to%20operate&f=false|title=What You See Is What You Hear: Creativity and Communication in Audiovisual Texts|author=Dario Martinelli|publisher=Springer Natur|year=2020|page=61}}</ref><ref name=\"Mark\">{{cite journal| last=Fox | first=Mark | year=2012| title=Space Invaders targets coins |journal= World Coin News |volume=39 |issue=2 |pages=35\u201337 |publisher=Krause Publications |url=https://www.academia.edu/2568838 |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> \n\nProduction of the 100 yen coin dropped going into the mid 1980's due to various proposed reasoning. Japan at the time had been in economic decline caused in part by trade tensions with other countries that were competing with Japanese exports.<ref name=\"Mark\"/> The Japanese government was trying to deflate the yen, and achieve more imports and less exports. Another explanation put forward is the introduction of the [[500 yen coin]] in 1982. The Japanese mint at the time stated that a higher value coin was needed for use in vending machines.<ref name=\"Mark\"/> In any case mintage figures recovered towards the very end of Emperor Sh\u014dwa's reign. Coin production remained unhindered during the early years of [[Akihito]]'s reign until the millennium, when 500 yen coins were turned out in record numbers. The offset caused low mintage numbers which included only 8,024,000 pieces struck in 2001, a record low for the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://global.rakuten.com/en/store/icoins/item/403992/|title=13, Heisei 1 yen a year, 50 yen, 100 yen rare thing three kinds are unused|work=Rakuten|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Composition==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Years \n! Material<ref name=\"circulation\"/> \n|-\n| 1957-1966 || 60% [[silver]], 30% [[copper]], 10% [[zinc]]\n|-\n| 1967\u2013Present || 75% copper, 25% [[nickel]]\n|}\n\n==Designs==\n<gallery>\nFile:100yen-S32.jpg|''Phoenix'' design (1957\u20131958)\nFile:100yen-S34.jpg|''Sheaf of rice'' design (1959\u20131966)\nFile:100JPY.JPG|''Sakura'' design (1967\u2013present)\n</gallery>\n\n==Circulation figures==\n===Sh\u014dwa===\n\nThe following are circulation dates which cover Emperor [[Hirohito]]'s reign. The dates below correspond with the 32nd to the 64th year (last) of his reign. One hundred yen coins had three main different designs, but there was no overlap in mintage between them. Coins for this period will all begin with the Japanese symbol [[Sh\u014dwa period|\u662d\u548c]] (Sh\u014dwa).\n\n*Japanese coins are read with a left to right format: \n:\"Emperors name\" \u2192 \"Number representing year of reign\" \u2192 \"Year\" (Ex: \u662d\u548c \u2192 53 \u2192 \u5e74).\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year of reign\n! [[Japanese calendar|Japanese date]]\n! [[Gregorian calendar|Gregorian date]]\n! Mintage<ref name=\"circulation\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mint.go.jp/WP_Vjp4V33Q/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/nenmeibetsuH31.R1.pdf|title=\u5e74\u9298\u5225\u8ca8\u5e63\u88fd\u9020\u679a\u6570|publisher=[[Japan Mint]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=March 25, 2019}}</ref>{{efn|name=mintage|Mintages on the Japan Mint website are in thousands}} \n|-\n| 32nd\n| \u4e09\u5341\u4e8c\n| 1957\n| 30,000,000\n|-\n| 33rd\n| \u4e09\u5341\u4e09\n| 1958\n| 70,000,000\n|-\n| 34th\n| \u4e09\u5341\u56db\n| 1959\n| 110,000,000\n|- \n| 35th\n| \u4e09\u5341\u4e94\n| 1960\n| 50,000,000\n|-\n| 36th\n| \u4e09\u5341\u516d\n| 1961\n| 15,000,000\n|-\n| 38th\n| \u4e09\u5341\u516b\n| 1963\n| 45,000,000\n|-\n| 39th\n| \u4e09\u5341\u4e5d \n| 1964{{efn|These were not issued as commemorative coins, those made for the Olympics can be found in [[#Commemoratives|their own section]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ngccoin.com/price-guide/world/japan-100-yen-y-78-yr.341959-yr.411966-cuid-1132859-duid-1442794|title=Japan 100 Yen Y# 78 Yr.39(1964)|work=Numismatic Guaranty Corporation|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>}}\n| 10,000,000\n|-\n| 40th\n| \u56db\u5341\n| 1965\n| 62,500,000\n|-\n| 41st\n| \u56db\u5341\u4e00\n| 1966\n| 97,500,000\n|-\n| 42nd\n| \u56db\u5341\u4e8c\n| 1967\n| 432,200,000\n|-\n| 43rd\n| \u56db\u5341\u4e09\n| 1968\n| 471,000,000\n|-\n| 44th\n| \u56db\u5341\u56db\n| 1969\n| 323,700,000\n|-\n| 45th\n| \u56db\u5341\u4e94\n| 1970\n| 237,100,000\n|-\n| 46th\n| \u56db\u5341\u516d\n| 1971\n| 481,050,000\n|-\n| 47th\n| \u56db\u5341\u4e03\n| 1972\n| 468,950,000\n|-\n| 48th\n| \u56db\u5341\u516b\n| 1973\n| 680,000,000\n|-\n| 49th\n| \u56db\u5341\u4e5d\n| 1974\n| 660,000,000\n|-\n| 50th\n| \u4e94\u5341\n| 1975\n| 437,160,000\n|-\n| 51st\n| \u4e94\u5341\u4e00 \n| 1976\n| 322,840,000\n|-\n| 52nd\n| \u4e94\u5341\u4e8c\n| 1977\n| 440,000,000\n|-\n| 53rd\n| \u4e94\u5341\u4e09\n| 1978\n| 292,000,000\n|-\n| 54th\n| \u4e94\u5341\u56db\n| 1979\n| 382,000,000\n|-\n| 55th\n| \u4e94\u5341\u4e94\n| 1980\n| 588,000,000\n|-\n| 56th\n| \u4e94\u5341\u516d\n| 1981\n| 348,000,000\n|-\n| 57th\n| \u4e94\u5341\u4e03\n| 1982\n| 110,000,000\n|-\n| 58th\n| \u4e94\u5341\u516b\n| 1983\n| 50,000,000\n|-\n| 59th\n| \u4e94\u5341\u4e5d\n| 1984\n| 41,850,000\n|-\n| 60th\n| \u516d\u5341\n| 1985\n| 58,150,000\n|-\n| 61st\n| \u516d\u5341\u4e00\n| 1986\n| 99,960,000\n|-\n| 62nd\n| \u516d\u5341\u4e8c \n| 1987\n| 193,775,000\n|-\n| 63rd\n| \u516d\u5341\u4e09 \n| 1988\n| 363,112,000\n|}\n\n===Heisei===\n\nThe following are circulation dates which cover Emperor [[Akihito]]'s reign. Akihito was crowned in 1989, which is marked with a \u5143 symbol on the coin as a one year type. Coins for this period all begin with the Japanese symbol [[Heisei period|\u5e73\u6210]] (Heisei).\n\n*Japanese coins are read with a left to right format: \n:\"Emperors name\" \u2192 \"Number representing year of reign\" \u2192 \"Year\" (Ex: \u5e73\u6210 \u2192 16 \u2192 \u5e74).\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year of reign\n! [[Japanese calendar|Japanese date]]\n! [[Gregorian calendar|Gregorian date]]\n! Mintage<ref name=\"circulation\"/>{{efn|name=mintage}}\n|-\n| 1st\n| \u5143 \n| 1989\n| 369,000,000\n|-\n| 2nd\n| \u4e8c\n| 1990\n| 444,953,000\n|-\n| 3rd\n| \u4e09\n| 1991\n| 375,120,000\n|-\n| 4th\n| \u56db\n| 1992\n| 211,130,000\n|-\n| 5th\n| \u4e94\n| 1993\n| 82,240,000\n|-\n| 6th\n| \u516d\n| 1994\n| 81,767,000\n|-\n| 7th\n| \u4e03\n| 1995\n| 92,874,000\n|-\n| 8th\n| \u516b\n| 1996\n| 237,213,000\n|-\n| 9th\n| \u4e5d\n| 1997\n| 272,086,000\n|-\n| 10th\n| \u5341 \n| 1998\n| 252,612,000\n|-\n| 11th\n| \u5341\u4e00 \n| 1999\n| 179,120,000\n|-\n| 12th\n| \u5341\u4e8c\n| 2000\n| 172,026,000\n|-\n| 13th\n| \u5341\u4e09\n| 2001\n| 8,024,000\n|-\n| 14th\n| \u5341\u56db\n| 2002\n| 10,667,000\n|-\n| 15th\n| \u5341\u4e94\n| 2003\n| 98,406,000\n|-\n| 16th\n| \u5341\u516d\n| 2004\n| 204,903,000\n|-\n| 17th\n| \u5341\u4e03\n| 2005\n| 300,029,000\n|-\n| 18th\n| \u5341\u516b\n| 2006\n| 216,594,000\n|-\n| 19th\n| \u5341\u4e5d\n| 2007\n| 129,904,000\n|-\n| 20th\n| \u4e8c\u5341\n| 2008\n| 93,811,000\n|-\n| 21st\n| \u4e8c\u5341\u4e00\n| 2009\n| 115,003,000\n|-\n| 22nd\n| \u4e8c\u5341\u4e8c\n| 2010\n| 67,905,000\n|-\n| 23rd\n| \u4e8c\u5341\u4e09\n| 2011\n| 178,936,000\n|-\n| 24th\n| \u4e8c\u5341\u56db\n| 2012\n| 402,211,000\n|-\n| 25th\n| \u4e8c\u5341\u4e94\n| 2013\n| 608,892,000\n|-\n| 26th\n| \u4e8c\u5341\u516d\n| 2014\n| 445,013,000\n|-\n| 27th\n| \u4e8c\u5341\u4e03\n| 2015\n| 410,004,000\n|-\n| 28th\n| \u4e8c\u5341\u516b\n| 2016\n| 461,064,000\n|-\n| 29th\n| \u4e8c\u5341\u4e5d \n| 2017\n| 518,927,000\n|-\n| 30th\n| \u4e09\u5341 \n| 2018\n| 567,960,000\n|-\n| 31st\n| {{lang|ja|\u4e09\u5341\u4e00}}\n| 2019\n| 302,006,000\n|}\n\n===Reiwa===\nThe following are circulation dates in the reign of the current Emperor. [[Naruhito]]'s [[Enthronement of the Japanese Emperor|accession]] to the [[Crysanthemum Throne]] took place on May 1, 2019 and he was formally enthroned on October 22, 2019. Coins for this period all begin with the Japanese symbol [[Reiwa period|\u4ee4\u548c]] (Reiwa). The inaugural year coin (2019) is marked \u5143 (first).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20190403/p2a/00m/0na/013000c|title=Japanese coins engraved with new era name 'Reiwa' likely to debut after summer|author=Shinpei Ide|work=[[Mainichi Shimbun]]|date=April 3, 2019|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year of reign\n! class=\"unsortable\"| [[Japanese calendar|Japanese date]]\n! [[Gregorian calendar|Gregorian date]]\n! Mintage<ref name=\"circulation\"/>{{efn|name=mintage}}\n|-\n| 1st\n| \u5143\n| 2019\n| 58,614,000\n|-\n| 2nd\n| \u4e8c\n| 2020\n| TBD\n|-\n|}\n\n==Commemoratives==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Image\n! class=\"unsortable\"| [[Japanese calendar|Japanese date]]\n! [[Gregorian calendar|Gregorian date]]\n! Mintage\n! Reason\n|-\n| [[File:100yen-S39Olympic.jpg|100px]]\n| align=\"center\"| \u4e09\u5341\u4e5d (39)<br>Sh\u014dwa{{efn|39th year of [[Emperor Sh\u014dwa]] (Hirohito)'s reign, [[Emperor Heisei]] ([[Akihito]]) was not crowned emperor until 1989}}\n| align=\"center\"| 1964\n| align=\"center\"| 80,000,000<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ngccoin.com/price-guide/world/japan-100-yen-y-79-yr.39-1964-cuid-1131923-duid-1442917|title=Japan 100 Yen Y# 